Thune=E2=80=99s Confirmation Calculus
-------------------------------

In recent days, as Senate Majority Leader John Thune
grappled with the purpose of his chamber=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cadvice and cons=
ent=E2=80=9D role for executive-branch nominees, he left open the possibili=
ty of letting Trump bypass confirmation votes altogether via recess appoint=
ments. Of course, doing so would deal a dramatic blow to what remains of co=
ngressional power, and neuter one of the upper chamber=E2=80=99s levers of =
influence over the incoming administration. But the current controversy ove=
r confirmation comes down to something more prosaic:
paperwork.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0

While Trump continues to demand confirmations on day one, many of his cabin=
et nominees haven=E2=80=99t even submitted ( https://www.politico.com/news/=
2025/01/08/trump-nominees-confirmation-senate-tensions-00197090?utm_campaig=
n=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F9%2F25%29&utm_content=
=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3De=
mail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) basic =
vetting materials, like financial disclosures, to the relevant Senate commi=
ttees, and the F.B.I.=E2=80=99s background checks have been delayed. Whethe=
r
or not the Senate will follow through on requiring final background checks =
is a live issue within the Republican conference, according to Politico. Su=
ch a situation puts every senator in the shoes of a hiring manager: If you =
hire a candidate without due diligence, you=E2=80=99re responsible for what=
ever misfortunes result. To wit: Judiciary Chairman Chuck Grassley postpone=
d the committee=E2=80=99s hearing with A.G. nominee Pam Bondi over a delaye=
d F.B.I. check.
Meanwhile, education secretary nominee Linda McMahon has yet to turn in her=
 paperwork, and aspiring D.N.I. Tulsi Gabbard has yet to furnish a pre-hear=
ing questionnaire.

For a senator, perhaps the most benign outcome of an irresponsible =E2=80=
=9Cyes=E2=80=9D vote is looking, ahem, stupid if new revelations about, say=
, Pete Hegseth or Gabbard surface after they=E2=80=99ve already been confir=
med to top national-security
posts. (Certainly, in Hegseth=E2=80=99s case, Trump=E2=80=99s team was repo=
rtedly =E2=80=9Cblindsided=E2=80=9D by allegations of sexual assault, which=
 the appointee has vigorously denied.) And the electoral consequences might=
 be minimal anyway=E2=80=94after all, who remembers which senators voted =
=E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D to confirm James Mattis or Mark Esper at the top of t=
he Pentagon?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But there are, of course, worse
scenarios: In the event of a terrorist attack or a fumbled government respo=
nse to some act of God (think former FEMA director Mike Brown, who was wide=
ly blamed for bungling the Bush administration=E2=80=99s response to Hurric=
ane Katrina), every senator who voted for that official without due diligen=
ce will have to own their decision at the ballot box. And if senators can=
=E2=80=99t be bothered to comb for potentially compromising information on =
national security nominees
now, America=E2=80=99s adversaries will be only too happy to do it themselv=
es later.

Indeed, this highlights one of the major differences between the modern Hou=
se and Senate. These days, House Republicans tend to do whatever is necessa=
ry in order to survive, which usually means avoiding the wrath of Trump. Bu=
t on the other side of the Capitol, there are still Republicans who think l=
ong and hard about their legacy. Why would they maneuver to protect
their advice-and-consent role for nominations, just to rubber stamp unvette=
d and unqualified candidates?=C2=A0

