ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In recent days, as Senate Majority Leader <stro=
ng>John Thune
</strong>grappled with the purpose of his chamber=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cadvice=
 and consent=E2=80=9D role for executive-branch nominees, he left open the =
possibility of letting Trump bypass confirmation votes altogether via reces=
s appointments. Of course, doing so would deal a <em>dramatic</em> blow to =
what remains of congressional power, and neuter one of the upper chamber=E2=
=80=99s levers of influence over the incoming administration. But the curre=
nt controversy over confirmation comes down to something more prosaic:
paperwork.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><b=
r/>While Trump continues to demand confirmations on day one, many of his ca=
binet nominees haven=E2=80=99t even <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/=
eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVVG52S245Q0xtTHRBNGlDYU1ocz0iLCJ=
ocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucG9saXRpY28uY29tL25ld3MvMjAyNS8wMS8wOC90cnVtcC1ub2=
1pbmVlcy1jb25maXJtYXRpb24tc2VuYXRlLXRlbnNpb25zLTAwMTk3MDkwP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
