MjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1UaGUrQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUkl=
CRVJTKyUyODElMkY3JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiL=
CJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwMzg4NDd9/9dfc2dc=
555c32ccf8d5c6c1b85aebe620059eca43eefe001ebc3e414cb0073ee" style=3D"text-de=
coration:underline;color:#d40000;">submitted</a> <em>basic</em> vetting mat=
erials, like financial disclosures, to the relevant Senate committees, and =
the F.B.I.=E2=80=99s background checks have been delayed. Whether
or not the Senate will follow through on requiring final background checks =
is a live issue within the Republican conference, according to Politico. Su=
ch a situation puts every senator in the shoes of a hiring manager: If you =
hire a candidate without due diligence, you=E2=80=99re responsible for what=
ever misfortunes result. To wit: Judiciary Chairman <strong>Chuck</strong> =
<strong>Grassley</strong> postponed the committee=E2=80=99s hearing with A.=
G. nominee <strong>Pam Bondi</strong> over a delayed F.B.I. check.
Meanwhile, education secretary nominee <strong>Linda McMahon</strong> has y=
et to turn in her paperwork, and aspiring D.N.I. <strong>Tulsi Gabbard</str=
ong> has yet to furnish a pre-hearing questionnaire. <br/><br/>For a senato=
r, perhaps the most benign outcome of an irresponsible =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=
=9D vote is looking, ahem, <em>stupid</em> if new revelations about, say, <=
strong>Pete Hegseth </strong>or Gabbard surface after they=E2=80=99ve alrea=
dy been confirmed to top national-security
posts. (Certainly, in Hegseth=E2=80=99s case, Trump=E2=80=99s team was repo=
rtedly =E2=80=9Cblindsided=E2=80=9D by allegations of sexual assault, which=
 the appointee has vigorously denied.) And the electoral consequences might=
 be minimal anyway=E2=80=94after all, who remembers which senators voted =
=E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D to confirm <strong>James Mattis </strong>or <strong>M=
ark Esper </strong>at the top of the Pentagon?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Bu=
t there are, of course, worse
scenarios: In the event of a terrorist attack or a fumbled government respo=
nse to some act of God (think former FEMA director <strong>Mike Brown</stro=
ng>, who was widely blamed for bungling the <strong>Bush </strong>administr=
ation=E2=80=99s response to Hurricane Katrina), every senator who voted for=
 that official without due diligence will have to own their decision at the=
 ballot box. And if senators can=E2=80=99t be bothered to comb for potentia=
lly compromising information on national security nominees
<em>now</em>, America=E2=80=99s adversaries will be only too happy to do it=
 themselves later.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Indeed, this highlights o=
ne of the major differences between the modern House and Senate. These days=
, House Republicans tend to do whatever is necessary in order to <em>surviv=
e</em>, which usually means avoiding the wrath of Trump. But on the <em>oth=
er</em> side of the Capitol, there are still Republicans who think long and=
 hard about their legacy. Why would they maneuver to protect
their advice-and-consent role for nominations, just to rubber stamp unvette=
d and unqualified candidates?=C2=A0</p></div>
